window.LESSON_CONTENT = {
  "1-1": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\n\nWelcome to the very beginning of your journey! Right now, Roblox Studio probably looks like the cockpit of a spaceship, filled with buttons, menus, and panels you don't understand yet. This lesson is simply about getting comfortable in the pilot's seat. We're going to learn how to look around, figure out where your game pieces live, change how they look, and finally, jump into the empty world you just started creating. By the end of this, you won't be intimidated by the screen anymore.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is how Roblox Studio organizes your workspace. Think of it like a giant art studio.\n\n**The Viewport (Your Canvas)**\nThe big 3D window right in the middle of your screen is called the Viewport. It's your window into the world you are building. When you aren't playing the game, you can fly around this space like a ghost, looking at your creations from any angle.\n\n**The Explorer (Your Filing Cabinet)**\nLook to the right side of your screen. The Explorer panel is literally a filing cabinet for your entire game. Every single thing that exists in your world\u2014the sky, the players, the ground, and every single block you place\u2014has a file folder here. If you ever lose something in the 3D world, you can always find its name in the Explorer.\n\n**The Properties Panel (Your Paintbrush & Toolbox)**\nIf the Explorer tells you *what* exists, the Properties panel tells you what it *looks and acts like*. Imagine clicking on a car in your Explorer; the Properties panel, usually located right below the Explorer, is where you'd go to see or change its color, its speed, or its weight. Every object has different properties you can tweak.\n\n**The Toolbox (The Toy Box)**\nYou might see a panel on the left called the Toolbox. This is a giant toy box filled with models, scripts, and audio that other players and Roblox have made. It's a great place to find inspiration, but since we are learning to be true developers, we are mostly going to build our own things from scratch.\n\n**Play, Run, and Stop**\nUp at the top of your screen are your magic buttons. The blue \"Play\" triangle drops your Roblox avatar right into the world so you can run around and test things. \"Run\" starts the game logic but leaves you in your ghost-camera view so you can watch things happen from above without spawning in. \"Stop\" is the red square that halts the simulation and pulls you back out into building mode.\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\n1. **Open a Fresh World:** Open Roblox Studio. Under the \"New\" tab, click on the **Baseplate** template . This gives us a flat, empty world with a spawn point to start with.\n2. **Bring Up Your Essential Panels:** Look at the tabs at the very top of your screen and click on **View**. Make sure the **Explorer** and **Properties** buttons are clicked (they will look darker or highlighted) . You'll see them dock on the right side of your screen.\n3. **Master the Camera:** Move your mouse into the big 3D Viewport. Hold down your **Right Mouse Button** and drag your mouse around\u2014this turns your virtual head. Now, *while* holding that right mouse button, use the **W, A, S, D** keys on your keyboard to fly forward, left, backward, and right. Try pressing **E** to fly straight up and **Q** to fly straight down!\n4. **Place Your First Block:** Click the **Home** tab at the top. Look for a button called **Part** (it usually looks like a cube) and click it. Boom! A block just dropped into the center of your world.\n5. **Change Its Look:** Click on the block you just placed in the Viewport (it will get a blue highlight). Now look over at your **Properties** panel on the bottom right. Find the row that says **BrickColor** and click the little color box next to it. Pick your favorite color.\n6. **Play Your Game:** In the Home tab, look for the blue triangle button that says **Play** and click it. You will spawn into your world as your Roblox character. Run over and look at the block you just made! When you're done, hit the red **Stop** button at the top of the screen to go back to building.\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **Getting lost in the void:** When you are first learning the WASD camera controls, it is *very* easy to accidentally fly too fast and suddenly find yourself staring at an endless grey sky, totally lost. Don't panic! Go to your Explorer window, click on any object you recognize (like \"SpawnLocation\" or the \"Part\" you made), and hover your mouse over the 3D Viewport, then press the **F** key on your keyboard. \"F\" stands for Focus, and it will instantly teleport your camera right to that object.\n* **Closing panels by accident:** It happens to absolutely everyone. You accidentally click the little 'x' on your Explorer or Properties window, the panel vanishes, and you feel like you broke Studio. Just remember the **View** tab at the very top of your screen. That tab controls everything you can *see* on your interface. Just click the Explorer or Properties button there to bring them right back.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/studio-overview](https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/studio-overview)\n A fantastic visual map of the entire Studio interface if you ever forget what a specific button or panel does.\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/camera-controls](https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/camera-controls)\n A quick cheat sheet for all the ways you can move your camera and navigate around your 3D world.## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\n\nWelcome to the very beginning of your journey! Right now, Roblox Studio probably looks like the cockpit of a spaceship, filled with buttons, menus, and panels you don't understand yet. This lesson is simply about getting comfortable in the pilot's seat. We're going to learn how to look around, figure out where your game pieces live, change how they look, and finally, jump into the empty world you just started creating. By the end of this, you won't be intimidated by the screen anymore.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is how Roblox Studio organizes your workspace. Think of it like a giant art studio.\n\n**The Viewport (Your Canvas)**\nThe big 3D window right in the middle of your screen is called the Viewport. It's your window into the world you are building. When you aren't playing the game, you can fly around this space like a ghost, looking at your creations from any angle.\n\n**The Explorer (Your Filing Cabinet)**\nLook to the right side of your screen. The Explorer panel is literally a filing cabinet for your entire game. Every single thing that exists in your world\u2014the sky, the players, the ground, and every single block you place\u2014has a file folder here. If you ever lose something in the 3D world, you can always find its name in the Explorer.\n\n**The Properties Panel (Your Paintbrush & Toolbox)**\nIf the Explorer tells you *what* exists, the Properties panel tells you what it *looks and acts like*. Imagine clicking on a car in your Explorer; the Properties panel, usually located right below the Explorer, is where you'd go to see or change its color, its speed, or its weight. Every object has different properties you can tweak.\n\n**The Toolbox (The Toy Box)**\nYou might see a panel on the left called the Toolbox. This is a giant toy box filled with models, scripts, and audio that other players and Roblox have made. It's a great place to find inspiration, but since we are learning to be true developers, we are mostly going to build our own things from scratch.\n\n**Play, Run, and Stop**\nUp at the top of your screen are your magic buttons. The blue \"Play\" triangle drops your Roblox avatar right into the world so you can run around and test things. \"Run\" starts the game logic but leaves you in your ghost-camera view so you can watch things happen from above without spawning in. \"Stop\" is the red square that halts the simulation and pulls you back out into building mode.\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\n1. **Open a Fresh World:** Open Roblox Studio. Under the \"New\" tab, click on the **Baseplate** template . This gives us a flat, empty world with a spawn point to start with.\n2. **Bring Up Your Essential Panels:** Look at the tabs at the very top of your screen and click on **View**. Make sure the **Explorer** and **Properties** buttons are clicked (they will look darker or highlighted) . You'll see them dock on the right side of your screen.\n3. **Master the Camera:** Move your mouse into the big 3D Viewport. Hold down your **Right Mouse Button** and drag your mouse around\u2014this turns your virtual head. Now, *while* holding that right mouse button, use the **W, A, S, D** keys on your keyboard to fly forward, left, backward, and right. Try pressing **E** to fly straight up and **Q** to fly straight down!\n4. **Place Your First Block:** Click the **Home** tab at the top. Look for a button called **Part** (it usually looks like a cube) and click it. Boom! A block just dropped into the center of your world.\n5. **Change Its Look:** Click on the block you just placed in the Viewport (it will get a blue highlight). Now look over at your **Properties** panel on the bottom right. Find the row that says **BrickColor** and click the little color box next to it. Pick your favorite color.\n6. **Play Your Game:** In the Home tab, look for the blue triangle button that says **Play** and click it. You will spawn into your world as your Roblox character. Run over and look at the block you just made! When you're done, hit the red **Stop** button at the top of the screen to go back to building.\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **Getting lost in the void:** When you are first learning the WASD camera controls, it is *very* easy to accidentally fly too fast and suddenly find yourself staring at an endless grey sky, totally lost. Don't panic! Go to your Explorer window, click on any object you recognize (like \"SpawnLocation\" or the \"Part\" you made), and hover your mouse over the 3D Viewport, then press the **F** key on your keyboard. \"F\" stands for Focus, and it will instantly teleport your camera right to that object.\n* **Closing panels by accident:** It happens to absolutely everyone. You accidentally click the little 'x' on your Explorer or Properties window, the panel vanishes, and you feel like you broke Studio. Just remember the **View** tab at the very top of your screen. That tab controls everything you can *see* on your interface. Just click the Explorer or Properties button there to bring them right back.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/studio-overview](https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/studio-overview)\n A fantastic visual map of the entire Studio interface if you ever forget what a specific button or panel does.\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/camera-controls](https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/camera-controls)\n A quick cheat sheet for all the ways you can move your camera and navigate around your 3D world.",
  "1-2": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\nIn the last lesson, you learned how to fly your camera around an empty world and drop a basic block. But a single grey block isn't a game. Today, we are building the actual starting area for your game\u2014a floating island. You're going to learn how to mold raw blocks into exactly the shape and look you want, how to defy gravity so your world doesn't fall into the endless void, and how to write your very first line of code to make a \"kill brick.\" This is where your empty canvas starts becoming a real, playable game.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is how to physically manipulate the pieces in your world. Think of parts like digital clay.\n\n**The Move, Scale, and Rotate Tools (The Modifiers)**\nWhen you select a part, you can use three main tools to change it:\n* **Move (Ctrl+2 or Cmd+2):** Gives you Red, Green, and Blue arrows. Grab an arrow to slide the part exactly along that axis.\n* **Scale (Ctrl+3 or Cmd+3):** Gives you little colored dots. Pulling them stretches the part to make it wider, taller, or longer.\n* **Rotate (Ctrl+4 or Cmd+4):** Gives you colored rings. Grabbing a ring spins the part around like a steering wheel.\n\n**Snapping (Digital Lego Bricks)**\nHave you ever tried to line two things up perfectly by hand, and one is just *slightly* off? Roblox prevents this using \"Snapping.\" By default, Roblox snaps your movements and rotations to an invisible grid (usually 1 stud for moving, and 45 degrees for rotating). It makes your parts click together cleanly, just like Lego bricks.\n\n**Anchoring (Defying Gravity)**\nThis is the most important checkbox in all of Roblox. By default, every part you place obeys physics. If you place a block in the sky and hit Play, it will fall. If you build a beautiful house and don't Anchor it, players can literally push the walls over. Checking the **Anchored** property locks the part frozen in space, completely ignoring gravity.\n\n**Dressing It Up: Material, Transparency, and Color**\nIn your Properties panel, you can change how a part looks. **Transparency** goes from 0 (solid) to 1 (completely invisible\u2014like glass or ghost blocks). For colors, Roblox gives you two options:\n* **BrickColor:** Think of this as a predefined box of 64 crayons. It's quick and easy (e.g., \"Really red\", \"Bright blue\").\n* **Color3:** This is the digital color wheel. It uses RGB (Red, Green, Blue) values, giving you access to millions of exact color shades.\n\n**The Kill Brick (Your First Code)**\nWe are going to make a red block that vaporizes players who step on it. To do this, we need a script. Here is the exact code we will use, read like a conversation:\n\n```luau\nlocal killBrick = script.Parent\n\nlocal function onTouch(otherPart)\n\tlocal character = otherPart.Parent\n\tlocal humanoid = character:FindFirstChild(\"Humanoid\")\n\t\n\tif humanoid then\n\t\thumanoid.Health = 0\n\tend\nend\n\nkillBrick.Touched:Connect(onTouch)\n```\n\nLet's walk through this line by line:\n* `local killBrick = script.Parent` -> We are storing the part the script is inside of into a variable called `killBrick` so we can easily talk to it.\n* `local function onTouch(otherPart)` -> We are creating a set of instructions (a function) and calling it `onTouch`. `otherPart` is whatever just touched our brick (like a player's toe).\n* `local character = otherPart.Parent` -> If a toe touched the brick, the \"Parent\" of that toe is the whole player Character model.\n* `local humanoid = character:FindFirstChild(\"Humanoid\")` -> We look inside the character for a \"Humanoid\". The Humanoid is a special Roblox object that gives players health and allows them to walk.\n* `if humanoid then` -> We are asking the game: \"Did we actually find a Humanoid?\" (Because maybe a random falling rock touched the brick, not a player).\n* `humanoid.Health = 0` -> If it *is* a player, we set their health to zero. Goodbye, player!\n* `killBrick.Touched:Connect(onTouch)` -> We are telling the game: \"Hey, whenever this brick's 'Touched' event happens, run that `onTouch` function we just made\".\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\nLet's build the starting platform for your game.\n\n1. **Spawn the Base:** In the top **Home** tab, click **Part** to drop a block into the Viewport.\n2. **Scale It Up:** Select the **Scale** tool from the top menu. Grab the colored dots and stretch this block out into a large, flat square (maybe 20 by 20 studs). This is the floor of your starting island.\n3. **ANCHOR IT!** With the floor selected, look at your **Properties** panel on the bottom right. Scroll down to the **Part** section and check the box next to **Anchored**.\n4. **Style the Island:** In the Properties panel, change the **Material** to `Grass` or `SmoothPlastic`. Then click the little box next to **Color** (the Color3 option) and pick a nice bright green or floating-island color.\n5. **Create the Kill Brick:** Click **Part** to spawn another block. Use the **Move** tool to drag it slightly to the edge of your starting platform.\n6. **Make it Look Dangerous:** In Properties, change its **BrickColor** to `Really red`, change its **Material** to `Neon` to make it glow, and make sure you check the **Anchored** box!\n7. **Add the Script:** Go to your **Explorer** panel on the right. Find your red part (you can right-click and rename it \"KillBrick\"). Hover over it, click the little `+` icon, and search for **Script**. Click to add it.\n8. **Paste the Code:** A new window will open. Delete the default `print(\"Hello world!\")` code. Type or paste the exact `killBrick` code from the section above into this script.\n9. **Test Your Trap:** Click the blue **Play** button at the top. Run around your beautiful anchored island. Then, step on the red neon brick. *Poof.*\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **The Z-Fighting Flicker:** If you ever place two parts so they occupy the exact same 3D space, their textures will glitch and flicker wildly. This is called \"Z-Fighting\" because the engine is fighting to decide which color to show on top. Always use the Move tool and Snapping to ensure parts sit *next* to each other, not inside each other.\n* **The \"Why is my game exploding?\" Panic:** I guarantee you that at some point this week, you will build an incredible, detailed house or vehicle, press Play, and watch it instantly collapse into a pile of rubble. 99.9% of the time, it's because you forgot to highlight your parts and check the **Anchored** box. Get in the habit of anchoring everything that isn't supposed to move!\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/building-and-visuals/studio-modeling/parts](https://create.roblox.com/docs/building-and-visuals/studio-modeling/parts)\n *The ultimate visual guide to every property a Part has, including materials and transparency.*\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/scripting/events](https://create.roblox.com/docs/scripting/events)\n *A great, plain-English breakdown of how Events (like `.Touched`) actually communicate with your code.*",
  "1-3": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\n\nIn our last lesson, you built a floating platform and a dangerous kill brick, but right now, they are just hovering in a gray, endless void. Today, we are going to build the actual world that your platform lives in. We'll use the Terrain Editor to sculpt a beautiful, natural island with mountains and rivers, and then we'll use the Lighting and Atmosphere settings to give it a specific, dramatic mood. This is where your game stops looking like a test block and starts looking like a real, breathing world.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is how Roblox handles **Terrain**. Unlike the blocky Parts we used in Lesson 2, Terrain is made of \"voxels.\" Think of it like digital Play-Doh. You don't resize it with dots; you sculpt it with brushes. You can add clay, carve it out, smooth the edges, or paint a new material right over the top of it.\n\nThe **Terrain Editor** is your main toolkit for this. It has a few main tools you'll constantly use:\n* **Generate:** This is your magic wand. Instead of building an entire island by hand, you give Roblox a size and a biome type (like Desert or Canyons), and it instantly generates a massive landscape for you .\n* **Add & Subtract:** Just like adding or scooping out lumps of clay.\n* **Paint:** This lets you swap materials without changing the physical shape. You can paint Sand near the water, and then paint Rock on the peaks of your mountains.\n\nNext, we have the **Sky & Lighting**. If you look in your Explorer, you'll see a folder called `Lighting`. This controls the sun, the shadows, and the overall color of your world. But light alone doesn't make a world feel real\u2014air does. By adding an `Atmosphere` object into your Lighting, you can create dense fog, heavy haze, and realistic scattering of sunlight . It turns a sterile, plastic-looking map into a moody, immersive environment.\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\nLet's generate your island, sculpt a mountain, and set the mood.\n\n1. **Open the Terrain Editor:** Go to the **Home** tab at the top of your screen and click on **Editor** (it has a little mountain and sun icon). This will open the Terrain Editor panel on the left side of your screen.\n2. **Generate Your Island Base:** In the Terrain Editor, click the **Create** tab, and then click **Generate**.\n * Under **Map Settings**, keep the position at `0, 0, 0` .\n * Under **Material Settings**, check the boxes for **Water**, **Sand**, and **Plains** .\n * Scroll down and click the blue **Generate** button. Watch as Roblox builds a massive island for you!\n3. **Sculpt a Mountain:** Now let's customize it. In the Terrain Editor, click the **Edit** tab and select the **Sculpt** tool.\n * Change the **Brush Mode** to `Add`.\n * Select the **Rock** material.\n * Click and drag your mouse around the middle of your island to build up a towering, rocky mountain.\n4. **Carve a River:** Still in the **Sculpt** tool, change the **Brush Mode** to `Subtract`. Drag your mouse from the base of your mountain all the way out to the ocean to carve a deep trench. Next, select the **Paint** tool, pick the **Water** material, and paint inside that trench to fill it with a flowing river.\n5. **Set the Mood with Lighting:** Let's make it a dramatic sunset. Go to your **Explorer** panel on the right and click on **Lighting**.\n * Down in the **Properties** panel, find `ClockTime` and type `17.5` (which is 5:30 PM). Watch the sky turn orange.\n6. **Add Atmosphere & Sun Rays:** Hover your mouse over `Lighting` in the Explorer, click the `+` icon, and search for **Atmosphere** . Add it.\n * Click the new Atmosphere object, go to Properties, and change the `Density` to `0.4` to give your island a thick, moody haze.\n * Click the `+` on Lighting again and add a **SunRaysEffect**. Now look at the sun\u2014you'll see gorgeous god-rays shining through your mountain peaks!\n7. **Move Your Lesson 2 Platform:** Finally, find the floating platform and KillBrick you made in Lesson 2 inside your Explorer. Use the **Move** tool to drag them right onto the beach of your new island.\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **The \"Smooth\" Tool is your best friend:** When you use the Add or Subtract tools, your terrain will look incredibly jagged and unnatural. Beginners often leave it like this. Always go back over your mountains and rivers with the **Smooth** tool. It acts like digital sandpaper and makes the landscape look organic and realistic .\n* **3D Grass only works on the \"Grass\" material:** If you want that beautiful, waving 3D grass in your game, you *must* paint the ground using the specific \"Grass\" material. Furthermore, you have to turn it on! Click on the `Terrain` object in your Explorer, go to Properties, and check the box that says **Decoration**. Boom\u2014instant fields of waving grass.\n* **Don't build huge terrain you don't need:** It is very tempting to use the Generate tool to make a map that is 10,000 studs wide. Don't do it. Voxel terrain takes up a lot of memory. Only generate the terrain that the player will actually see and interact with, or your game will become very laggy for players on older phones.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/environment/terrain](https://create.roblox.com/docs/environment/terrain)\n *The ultimate guide to mastering the Terrain Editor, including advanced brush settings and sea-level tools.*\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/environment/lighting](https://create.roblox.com/docs/environment/lighting)\n *A deep dive into how Lighting, Atmosphere, and Post-Processing effects work together to create stunning visuals.*",
  "1-4": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\n\nNow that you have a beautifully sculpted island with a floating platform and a dangerous kill brick, your game is going to get messy very fast if you just keep throwing blocks everywhere. This lesson is really about *organization*. We are going to learn how Roblox structures your world behind the scenes, how to bundle pieces together so your workspace doesn't look like a spilled bucket of Lego bricks, and how to control exactly where players appear when they join your game.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is how Roblox stores all your stuff. We call this the **DataModel**, but you can just think of it as a giant family tree.\n\n**The DataModel Tree (Your Explorer Panel)**\nWhen you look at the **Explorer** panel on the right side of your screen, you are looking at the DataModel. At the very top is the `game` itself. Inside the game are major folders (Services) like `Workspace` (the physical 3D world you see) , `Lighting` (the sky and sun we tweaked in Lesson 3), and `Players`. Whenever you place a part in the 3D view, it is automatically placed as a \"child\" inside the `Workspace` folder.\n\n\n\n**Grouping into Models (Digital Super Glue)**\nIf you build a house out of 100 parts, your Workspace will list 100 individual \"Part\" items. That is a nightmare to scroll through. Instead, you can select them all and group them into a **Model**. Think of a Model like a cardboard box that holds related parts together. It keeps your Explorer clean and lets you move the entire house at once.\n\n**Naming Objects: Why Scripts Care**\nIf you name everything \"Part\", your code will get incredibly confused. Imagine walking into a classroom of 30 kids and shouting, \"Hey, kid!\" You need specific names. If you name a model `FloatingPlatform`, you can tell your script exactly where to look in the family tree:\n```luau\n-- This is how modern Luau code finds your specific model\nlocal platform = workspace.FloatingPlatform\n```\n\n**The SpawnLocation**\nWhen you hit Play, where does your character fall from the sky? By default, Roblox drops you in the dead center of the world. A **SpawnLocation** is a special type of part that acts as a landing pad. Whenever a player joins or dies, the game searches the DataModel for a SpawnLocation and drops the player right on top of it.\n\n\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\nLet's build a path of stepping stones connecting your island's beach to the floating platform from Lesson 2, and set up a proper spawn point!\n\n1. **Place Your SpawnLocation:** Look at the **Model** tab at the top of your screen. Look for the button that looks like a sunburst pad and says **Spawn**. Click it. Use the **Move** tool to place this pad securely on the beach of your island.\n2. **Build a Stepping Stone:** Go to the **Home** tab, click **Part**, and create a flat, wooden plank (maybe 4 studs wide and 6 studs long). Use the Properties panel to change its Material to `Wood` and color it brown.\n3. **Add Detail to the Stone:** Add two smaller cylinder parts to act as little support beams underneath the plank. Now you have a stepping stone made of 3 distinct parts.\n4. **Group It into a Model:** Hold down **Shift** and click all 3 parts of your stepping stone in the Viewport (or in the Explorer) to highlight them all. Press **Ctrl + G** (or Cmd + G on Mac) on your keyboard. You will see them instantly collapse into a `Model` icon in your Explorer!\n5. **Rename the Model:** In the Explorer, click on your new Model and press **F2** on your keyboard (or right-click -> Rename) . Name it `SteppingStone_1`. *Teacher tip: Don't use spaces in the name!*\n6. **Anchor the Parts Inside:** Select `SteppingStone_1` in the Explorer, then look at the Properties panel. You might notice there is no \"Anchored\" checkbox! **A Model itself cannot be anchored.** You must click the little arrow next to the Model to open it, select the 3 parts *inside* the model, and check **Anchored** for them.\n7. **Duplicate and Place:** Select your `SteppingStone_1` model. Press **Ctrl + D** (Cmd + D) to duplicate it. Move the new model forward to create a path. Press **F2** and rename this one `SteppingStone_2`. Do this one more time to create `SteppingStone_3`, leading right up to your floating platform from Lesson 2.\n8. **Test the Flow:** Press the blue **Play** button. You should spawn directly on the beach pad you placed in Step 1. Jump across your neatly organized `SteppingStone` models, and make your way to the floating platform!\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **Models are Folders, Not Glue:** The absolute biggest mistake beginners make is thinking that pressing `Ctrl + G` to group parts physically glues them together. It does not. Grouping is strictly for *organization*. If you group a car together but forget to anchor the parts inside, the car will explode into a dozen pieces the second you press Play.\n* **The Invisible Spawn Trick:** Beginners often think they are stuck with that ugly grey sunburst decal on their SpawnLocations. You aren't! Click the `SpawnLocation`, go to the Explorer, click the little arrow next to it, and delete the `Decal` inside. Then, in Properties, set the SpawnLocation's `Transparency` to `1`. Boom. Now players will spawn gracefully on your sandy beach without seeing an ugly plastic pad!\n* **Parenting vs Grouping:** Sometimes you don't need a Model. If you have a desk and a coffee cup, you can just drag the coffee cup *inside* the desk part in the Explorer. The desk becomes the \"Parent\" of the cup. If you delete the desk, the cup gets deleted too.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/workspace/models](https://create.roblox.com/docs/workspace/models)\n *The official guide on how Models work, including how to set a \"PrimaryPart\" for moving complex models via code.*\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/building-and-visuals/studio-modeling/spawn-locations](https://create.roblox.com/docs/building-and-visuals/studio-modeling/spawn-locations)\n *Everything you need to know about SpawnLocations, including how to use them for team-based games later on.*",
  "2-5": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\nWelcome to Phase 2! So far, you've sculpted a beautiful island and organized it with models and spawn points. But right now, your world is frozen. It just sits there. This lesson is really about giving your world a brain. We're going to learn how to write your very first lines of code so that the platforms you built in previous lessons can actually think, communicate, and change on their own.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nBefore we start typing, we need to understand the tools we are working with. Think of scripting like writing a recipe for the game to follow.\n\n**Script vs LocalScript vs ModuleScript**\nRoblox has three main types of scripts, and mixing them up is a classic beginner mistake:\n* **Script (Server Script):** This runs on the Roblox server. If this script changes the color of a block, *everyone* playing the game sees it change. It is the \"God mode\" script.\n* **LocalScript:** This runs only on the individual player's device (their client). If a LocalScript changes a block's color, *only that specific player* sees it change. We use these for things like UI buttons and player camera controls.\n* **ModuleScript:** Think of this as a rulebook or a storage box for code. It doesn't run on its own; it just holds functions and variables that your other scripts can \"borrow\" so you don't have to write the same code twice.\n\n**Where to Put Scripts**\nWhere a script lives changes how it behaves. If you want a script to control the whole game (like keeping score), you put it in a special folder called `ServerScriptService`. But if you want a script to control *just one specific object* (like a trap door or a platform), you place it directly inside that object in the Explorer.\n\n**script.Parent (Finding Yourself)**\nWhen you put a script inside a block, the script needs to know how to talk to that block. We use the keyword `script` to mean \"me\". We use the word `Parent` to mean \"the object holding me\". So, `script.Parent` translates to: \"The object that I am inside of.\"\n\n**The Output Window & print()**\nIf your script breaks, how does it tell you? Through the **Output** window. This is a panel where the game talks to you. You can also force the game to talk to you using the `print()` command. It literally prints whatever you type into that Output window so you can see what your code is thinking.\n\n**Comments (--)**\nSometimes you want to leave a sticky note in your code for yourself to read later. If you type two dashes (`--`), the computer will completely ignore the rest of that line. We call this a comment.\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\nLet's make one of your platforms wake up, tell you its name, and magically change color.\n\n**Step 1: Open the Output Window**\nYou cannot code without seeing the Output window. Go to the very top of your screen, click the **View** tab, and click the **Output** button. A new panel will appear at the bottom of your screen.\n\n**Step 2: Add Your Script**\nLook in your **Explorer** on the right. Find one of the platforms or stepping stones you made in Lesson 4. Hover over the part, click the little `+` icon, and search for **Script**. Click it to add it.\n\n**Step 3: Write the Code**\nA new tab will open in the middle of your screen with `print(\"Hello world!\")`. Delete that. Type this exact code into your script:\n\n```luau\n-- 1. Grab the platform this script is inside of\nlocal platform = script.Parent\n\n-- 2. Tell us the name of the platform in the Output window\nprint(\"I am controlling: \" .. platform.Name)\n\n-- 3. Wait for 3 seconds so we can actually see it happen\ntask.wait(3)\n\n-- 4. Change the color of the platform\nplatform.BrickColor = BrickColor.new(\"Bright blue\")\n```\n\n**Let's read this code together:**\n* Line 2: We use the `local` keyword to create a variable named `platform`. We assign it to `script.Parent` so we never have to type `script.Parent` again.\n* Line 5: We use `print()` to send a message to the Output window. The `..` symbol glues our text together with the actual `Name` property of our platform.\n* Line 8: `task.wait(3)` tells the script to freeze and wait for exactly 3 seconds before moving to the next line.\n* Line 11: We look at the `BrickColor` property of our platform and set it to a brand new color: `\"Bright blue\"`.\n\n**Step 4: Run the Game**\nGo to the **Home** tab at the top. Click the little arrow under **Play** and select **Run** (this starts the game without spawning your character).\nLook down at your **Output** window. You should see a message saying exactly what part it is controlling. Count to 3, and watch your platform instantly turn blue!\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **The Output Window is your best friend:** Beginners often close the Output window because it takes up screen space. *Never do this while scripting.* If you misspell a word, your code will break, and the Output window is the *only* place that will show you the red error text telling you exactly which line you messed up.\n* **Lua is strictly Case-Sensitive:** If you type `script.parent` (lowercase 'p'), your code will break. If you type `brickcolor` instead of `BrickColor`, your code will break. Capitalization matters immensely in programming. If something isn't working, check your capital letters first!\n* **BrickColor vs Color3:** In the Properties panel, you might notice a property called `Color` and another called `BrickColor`. They are different! `BrickColor` is like a box of 64 named crayons (e.g., \"Bright blue\"). `Color3` uses RGB numbers to make millions of custom colors. In code, you cannot mix them. `platform.BrickColor = Color3.new(...)` will throw an error.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/tutorials/scripting/basic-scripting/intro-to-scripting](https://create.roblox.com/docs/tutorials/scripting/basic-scripting/intro-to-scripting)\n *The perfect official follow-up tutorial that reinforces variables and changing properties.*\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/output-window](https://create.roblox.com/docs/studio/output-window)\n *A guide on how to read the Output window and use it to debug your future scripts.*",
  "2-6": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\n\nIn your previous lessons, you hard-coded the exact color and size of your platforms by typing them straight into the Properties panel or the script. But what if you want a platform to grow every time a player touches it? Or what if you want to keep track of a player's score? You can't do that with frozen, hard-coded numbers. This lesson is really about **Variables and Data Types**. We are going to learn how to create digital \"storage boxes\" to hold information, how to do math with that information, and how to change your world dynamically while the game is running.\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is what a variable actually is. Imagine you are looking at several containers of ice cream. How do you know what flavor is inside without tasting it? You look at the label on the container . A **variable** is exactly that\u2014a labeled container that holds a piece of information so your script can remember it and use it later.\n\nTo create one, we *always* use the keyword `local`. `local` means this box stays right here in this specific script, keeping your game's memory clean and preventing it from interfering with other scripts. If you don't use `local`, the variable becomes \"global,\" meaning any script anywhere can accidentally mess with it, which causes massive headaches later.\n\nNow, what can we put inside these boxes? In Luau, we have different **Data Types**:\n* **`string`**: This is just text. We always wrap it in quotation marks so the computer knows it's reading words, like `\"Hello!\"`.\n* **`number`**: Just numbers. No quotes needed. It handles whole numbers like `5` and decimals like `3.14`.\n* **`boolean`**: A simple true or false. Think of it like a light switch: `true` is on, `false` is off.\n* **`nil`**: This literally means \"nothing\" or \"empty.\" If a variable equals `nil`, the box has nothing inside it.\n\n**Math and Gluing Things Together**\nBecause variables hold data, we can do math with them! We use standard math operators: `+` for addition, `-` for subtraction, `*` for multiplication, `/` for division, `^` for exponents, and `%` to find the remainder of a division .\n\nBut what if you want to combine a `string` (text) and a `number`? If you try to do math on a word, Roblox will throw an error. Instead, we use **String Concatenation**, which is two dots (`..`). This acts like digital glue to stick a word and a number together . Sometimes, to be perfectly safe, we use `tostring(5)` to force a number to act like a word, or `tonumber(\"5\")` to force a word to act like a number before gluing or doing math.\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\nLet's write a script that stores a multiplier in a variable, waits a few seconds, and then uses math to drastically resize and move one of the stepping stones you built in Lesson 4!\n\n1. **Find Your Platform:** Go to your **Explorer** panel. Find one of your `SteppingStone` models, click the arrow to open it, and select the main Part inside it.\n2. **Add the Script:** Hover over that Part, click the `+` icon, and add a **Script**. Delete the `print(\"Hello world!\")` line.\n3. **Write the Code:** Type this exact code with me.\n\n```luau\n-- 1. Grab the platform we are inside of\nlocal platform = script.Parent\n\n-- 2. Wait 3 seconds so we can load into the game and watch!\ntask.wait(3)\n\n-- 3. Let's set up our variables (our labeled containers)\nlocal creatorName = \"Architect\"\nlocal scaleMultiplier = 3\nlocal isMagic = true\n\n-- 4. Glue our strings and variables together to print a message\nprint(creatorName .. \" is growing the platform! Magic status: \" .. tostring(isMagic))\n\n-- 5. CHALLENGE: Resize the platform 3x using our variable!\nlocal currentSize = platform.Size\nplatform.Size = currentSize * scaleMultiplier\n\n-- 6. Move the platform up dynamically using math\nlocal currentPosition = platform.Position\nplatform.Position = currentPosition + Vector3.new(0, 10, 0)\n```\n\n**Let's read this code together, line by line:**\n* Lines 2 & 5: We create a `local` variable for our platform, then tell the script to `task.wait(3)` seconds so we have time to spawn in and watch the magic happen.\n* Lines 8-10: We declare three variables of different data types. `creatorName` is a `string`. `scaleMultiplier` is a `number`. `isMagic` is a `boolean`.\n* Line 13: We use `print()` to send a message to our **Output** window. Notice how we use `..` to glue `\"Architect\"` to the rest of the text. We wrap `isMagic` in `tostring()` to safely convert the boolean `true` into a readable word. Modern Luau also lets you do this with backticks like ``print(`{creatorName} is growing the platform!`)``, but `..` is the classic way you'll see everywhere.\n* Lines 16-17: **The Challenge!** We grab the platform's current size (which is a 3D size, meaning length, width, and height) and store it in `currentSize`. Then, we multiply that entire size by our `scaleMultiplier` (which holds the number 3).\n* Lines 20-21: We do the same thing for the position! We find out where it currently is, and we use the `+` math operator to add 10 studs of height to its Y-axis (`Vector3.new(0, 10, 0)`).\n\n4. **Test it Out:** Click **Play** at the top of your screen. Open your **Output** window (View > Output). Run over to your stepping stone. Count to 3, and watch it instantly triple in size and jump 10 studs into the air!\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **Using `+` instead of `..` for text:** If you know JavaScript or Python, you are probably used to writing `print(\"Score: \" + 10)`. If you do that in Luau, your game will break! In Luau, the `+` operator is *strictly* for math. If you want to put two pieces of text together, you must use the `..` concatenation operator .\n* **Forgetting `local`:** It is so incredibly tempting to just type `myScore = 10` instead of `local myScore = 10`. Without `local`, you are creating a \"global\" variable. If you have 5 different scripts that all accidentally use the word `myScore`, they will constantly overwrite each other, and your game will behave completely randomly. Always, always write `local` first.\n* **Capitalization and typos in Variables:** If you name your variable `scaleMultiplier`, but later you try to type `platform.Size = currentSize * scalemultiplier` (with a lowercase 's'), the Output window will scream at you. To the computer, `scaleMultiplier` and `scalemultiplier` are two completely different boxes.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/scripting/variables](https://create.roblox.com/docs/scripting/variables)\n *The absolute best guide for understanding exactly how variables store information in memory.*\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/luau/types](https://create.roblox.com/docs/luau/types)\n *A great breakdown of every data type that exists in Luau, including strings, booleans, and numbers.*",
  "2-7": "## \ud83e\udded What This Is Really About\n\nIn your previous lessons, you used variables to make a stepping stone grow, but it grew *every single time* no matter what. Real games need to make decisions. If a player has a key, open the door; if they don't, keep it locked. This lesson is about teaching your game how to think and choose between different outcomes using \"conditions.\" We are going to revisit the KillBrick you made in Lesson 2 and make it smart enough to change its own appearance based on the choices it makes. Your world is about to get logic!\n\n## \ud83d\udcd6 The Concepts, Explained Like a Teacher\n\nSo the first thing you need to understand is how a script asks a question. Think of conditional statements like a digital bouncer at a club checking IDs.\n\n**The `if` / `elseif` / `else` Bouncer**\nTo ask a question, we use the `if` keyword. If the answer is true, the script executes the code inside the block .\n* **`if`**: The first rule. \"If you are wearing a red shirt, come in.\"\n* **`elseif`**: The backup rule. \"If you aren't wearing red, but you *are* wearing blue, you get a discount.\"\n* **`else`**: The catch-all bucket. \"Otherwise, if you don't fit any of the rules above, go home.\"\n\n**Comparison Operators (Asking the Question)**\nTo compare two things, we use math symbols .\n* `==` means \"Is exactly equal to\" (Notice there are two equals signs! This is very important).\n* `~=` means \"Is NOT equal to\" .\n* `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=` are your standard greater than / less than symbols .\n\n**Logical Operators (Combining Questions)**\nSometimes one question isn't enough. We use **`and`**, **`or`**, and **`not`** to link questions together . For example: `if isRed and isGlowing then...` means *both* things must be true.\n\n**The Luau Truth Rule (The Weird Part)**\nIn some coding languages, the number `0` or an empty word `\"\"` means \"false.\" In Luau, *everything* evaluates to `true` except the actual word `false` and `nil` (which means empty/nothing) . That means if you ask Luau `if 0 then`, the computer will say \"Yes, that is true!\" .\n\n**Nested Conditions**\nThis is simply asking a question *inside* of another question. \"If it's a car, then... is the engine running?\"\n\n## \ud83d\udee0\ufe0f Let's Build It \u2014 Step by Step\n\nLet's make your KillBrick from Lesson 2 check its own color and decide how to disguise itself when the game starts.\n\n1. **Find Your KillBrick:** Go to your **Explorer** panel. Find the KillBrick you placed on your island's beach back in Lesson 2.\n2. **Add a Setup Script:** Hover over the KillBrick, click the `+` icon, and add a new **Script**. Let's name this script `TrapLogic` so you don't confuse it with your touch script.\n3. **Write the Code:** Delete the default `print` line and type exactly this. We are going to use modern string interpolation (the backticks) to inject our variables right into our text!\n\n```luau\n-- 1. Grab the part we are inside of\nlocal killBrick = script.Parent\n\n-- 2. Wait 2 seconds so we can spawn in and watch it happen!\ntask.wait(2)\n\n-- 3. Print a warning using modern string interpolation\nprint(`Danger! The trap {killBrick.Name} is thinking...`)\n\n-- 4. Let's ask our first question: Is it Red?\nif killBrick.BrickColor == BrickColor.new(\"Really red\") then\n\t\n\t-- If it IS red, make it glow ominously\n\tkillBrick.Transparency = 0.3\n\tprint(\"Condition met: The trap is red! Adding transparency.\")\n\t\n\t-- 5. A Nested Condition: Let's ask a question INSIDE our question\n\tif killBrick.Material == Enum.Material.Neon then\n\t\tprint(\"Nested condition met: It's also Neon! Super dangerous.\")\n\tend\n\n-- 6. The Backup Rule: What if it's Blue instead?\nelseif killBrick.BrickColor == BrickColor.new(\"Bright blue\") then\n\tkillBrick.Transparency = 0.8\n\tprint(\"Condition met: It's a stealthy blue trap.\")\n\n-- 7. The Catch-All: If it's NOT red, and NOT blue...\nelse\n\t-- Disguise it as an innocent wooden block!\n\tkillBrick.BrickColor = BrickColor.new(\"Brown\")\n\tkillBrick.Material = Enum.Material.Wood\n\tprint(\"Catch-all met: Disguising the trap as normal wood!\")\nend\n```\n\n**Let's read this code together:**\n* Line 8: We use backticks `` ` `` to create our string, and `{killBrick.Name}` dynamically inserts the name of the brick right into the text!\n* Line 11: `if killBrick.BrickColor == ... then`. We are using double equals `==` to ask the game: \"Are you *exactly* this color?\" .\n* Line 14: Because the statement was true, we change the transparency.\n* Line 18: We put an `if` inside of an `if` (a nested condition). We only ask if it's Neon *if* we already know it's red.\n* Lines 23 & 28: If the brick wasn't red, it checks the `elseif`. If it wasn't blue either, it drops into the `else` bucket and disguises itself as wood .\n\n4. **Test Your Logic:** Click **Play**. Since you made your KillBrick `Really red` and `Neon` in Lesson 2, you will see the transparency drop to `0.3` and see both print statements in your **Output** window.\n5. **Change the Outcome:** Hit the red **Stop** button. Select your KillBrick and use the **Properties** panel to change its color to \"Bright yellow\". Hit **Play** again. Watch the script hit the `else` block and instantly turn your yellow brick into a wooden block!\n\n## \ud83d\udca1 The Real Lessons (What Trips Beginners Up)\n\n* **`=` vs `==` (The Classic Blunder):** A single equals sign `=` is an *action*\u2014it means \"I am giving you this value\" (like `Transparency = 0.3`) . A double equals `==` is a *question*\u2014it means \"Are these two things the same?\" . If you write `if killBrick.Transparency = 0.3 then`, Roblox will completely break.\n* **Forgetting `then` or `end`:** Human brains read \"If it's red, make it glow.\" But the computer needs perfect bookends. Every `if` and `elseif` *must* be followed by the word `then`, and the entire block *must* be closed with the word `end` at the very bottom . If your code has a red underline, you probably missed an `end`.\n* **The \"Wait, 0 is True?\" Trap:** If you ever write `local health = 0`, and later write `if health then`, the game will say \"Yes, health is true!\" Because in Luau, the number `0` is a real thing, and therefore it is \"true\" . Always write `if health > 0 then` instead.\n\n## \ud83d\udd17 Go Deeper \u2014 Official Roblox Docs\n\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/luau/control-structures](https://create.roblox.com/docs/luau/control-structures)\n *The official breakdown of how if/then control structures direct the flow of your game.*\n* [https://create.roblox.com/docs/luau/operators](https://create.roblox.com/docs/luau/operators)\n *Keep this bookmarked! A perfect cheat sheet for all the math and logical operators (`==`, `~=`, `and`, `or`) you'll ever need.*"
};
